05824nam a22007935i 9780271094182DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710941827 a10.1515/97802710941822doi  a(DE-B1597)627724  a(OCoLC)1312148974  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBX7637b.L56 2022 7aREL0880002bisacsh04a289.6223/eng/202204271 aLindman, Janet Moore, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Vivifying Spirit :bQuaker Practice and Reform in Antebellum America /cJanet Moore Lindman. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (284 p.) :b6 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of Abbreviations -- tAuthor’s Note: Dating System of the Religious Society of Friends -- tIntroduction: Practical Friends -- tPart 1. Seed Time -- t1 “Inward and Outward Consolation”: Quaker Piety -- t2 “To Cultivate Tender Minds”: Educating Children -- t3 “The Solemn Close”: Rituals of Death -- tPart 2. Fruitless Exercise and Distress -- t4 “A Dividing and Separating Spirit”: The Hicksite Schism -- t5 “Contentions, Divisions, and Subdivisions”: Gurneyites v. Wilburites -- t6 “Practical Righteousness”: Reforming Friends -- tPart 3. A Work of Redemption -- t7 “In the Advancement of Piety”: Quaker Manuscript and Print Culture -- t8 “Tokens of Remembrance”: Friends, Memory, and History -- tConclusion: American Quakerisms -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAmerican Quakerism changed dramatically in the antebellum era owing to both internal and external forces, including schism, industrialization, western migration, and reform activism. With the “Great Separation” of the 1820s and subsequent divisions during the 1840s and 1850s, new Quaker sects emerged. Some maintained the quietism of the previous era; others became more austere; still others were heavily influenced by American evangelicalism and integration into modern culture. Examining this increasing complexity and highlighting a vital religiosity driven by deeply held convictions, Janet Moore Lindman focuses on the Friends of the mid-Atlantic and the Delaware Valley to explore how Friends’ piety affected their actions—not only in the evolution of religious practice and belief but also in response to a changing social and political context. Her analysis demonstrates how these Friends’ practical approach to piety embodied spiritual ideals that reformulated their religion and aided their participation in a burgeoning American republic.Based on extensive archival research, this book sheds new light on both the evolution of Quaker spiritual practice and the history of antebellum reform movements. It will be of interest to scholars and students of early American history, religious studies, and Quaker studies as well as general readers interested in the history of the Society of Friends.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aChurch renewalxSociety of FriendsxHistoryy19th century. 0aQuakerszPennsylvaniaxHistoryy19th century. 0aQuakerszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSociety of FriendszPennsylvaniaxHistoryy19th century. 0aSociety of FriendszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aSpiritualityxSociety of FriendsxHistoryy19th century. 7aRELIGION / Christianity / Quaker.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE